++- Criterion 3 [hero - Proof Replay]: Direction is right, spec is not strong enough. Hover-to-highlight is useful, but not unforgettable. The wow must be a guided “challenge any sentence” proof replay with chain-of-custody and signature meaning.
++- Criterion 4 [visual & motion system]: Good foundation, under-specified for Linear/Stripe/Vercel-tier craft. Needs concrete component specs, density modes, responsive layouts, and exact state behavior. Vercel’s own interface guidance stresses no dead ends, all states, stable skeletons, and redundant status cues. ([vercel.com](https://vercel.com/design/guidelines?utm_source=openai))
++- Criterion 5 [liveliness]: Still too hand-wavy. Durations are not a motion system. The plan needs storyboards for proof reveal, run progress, source settling, count changes, empty states, and reduced-motion equivalents.
++- Criterion 6 [per-page targets]: Several C to S jumps are unrealistic without naming rebuilds. Intake, report/inspector, graph, and export need structural redesign, not polish.
++- Criterion 7 [differentiation]: Partly holds, but overclaims. Elicit links claims/extractions to exact quotes, Scite shows citation context, Consensus has meters/tables/graphs. POLARIS’s defensible uniqueness is signed, independently evaluated, per-sentence, offline-verifiable proof. ([elicit.com](https://elicit.com/solutions/literature-review?utm_source=openai)) ([scite.ai](https://scite.ai/?utm_source=openai)) ([help.consensus.app](https://help.consensus.app/en/articles/11954907-consensus-product-changelog?utm_source=openai))
